{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}
{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}
'''Miles Peter Andrews''' (1742 – 18 July 1814) was an 18th-century English playwright, gunpowder manufacturer and politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1796 to 1814.

==Biography==
[[File:Drury lane facade 1775.png|right|thumb|upright|Drury Lane Theatre in 1775]]
Andrews was the son of William Andrews, a drysalter of Watling Street and his wife Catherine Pigou. After helping his father in business in the day time, he was "accustomed to sally forth in the evening with sword and bag to [[Ranelagh Gardens|Ranelagh]] or some other public place". He gradually made useful social connections and became a constant companion of [[George Lyttelton, 2nd Baron Lyttelton|Lord Lyttelton]]. He wrote plays musicals and operas. The first was performed at [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]] in 1774. In 1775 the opera diva [[Ann Cargill]] aged 15 ran away with him and she then had to be restrained at home by a court order. Andrews had several further plays performed at the [[Haymarket Theatre|Haymarket]]. Andrews lived in a mansion at [[Green Park]] where he entertained the fashionable society of London, and was a member of several clubs.<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Andrews, Miles Peter}}</ref>

With his uncle [[Pigou|Frederick Pigou]], a director of the [[British East India Company]], Andrews became the owner of an extensive [[gunpowder]] factory at Hawley Mills on the [[River Darent]] at [[Dartford]], [[Kent]].
[[George Colman the Younger]] described Andrews as "one of the most persevering poetical pests", and his plays as "like his powder mills, particularly hazardous affairs, and in great danger of going off with a sudden and violent explosion".<ref>[http://archive.thepoultrykeeper.co.uk/search/results.php?g_seller_id=445&g_orderby=authoraz&g_offset=40 Rarebooksinternational.com]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} -</ref><ref>[http://ukbookworld.com/cgi-bin/search.pl?s_i_DLR_ID=fenbooks&all=1 UK Book World]</ref> This was no idle comparison as an explosion occurred in October 1790.<ref>''The World''  14 October 1790</ref>

:"Between four and five o'clock this afternoon (October 12th 1790) the people here, and in the neighbourhood, were terribly alarmed by the blowing up of Mr Pegu (sic)'s Powder Mills, within a short mile of this town.."

In 1796 Andrews succeeded Lord Lyttleton as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bewdley (UK Parliament constituency)|Bewdley]] which he represented until his death in 1814.<ref name=HOP>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1790-1820/member/andrews-miles-peter-1742-1814 History of Parliament Online - Miles Peter Andrews]</ref> There is a memorial to him in [[St James's Church, Piccadilly]].
[[File:St James's South and east fronts 1814 edited.jpg|thumb|right|upright|St James's Piccadilly in 1815.]]

==Works==
* ''The Conjuror - a farce'' -  [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]] 1774
* ''The Election - a musical interlude'' - Drury Lane 1774
* ''Belphegor, or the Wishes, a comic opera'' - Drury Lane 1778
* ''Summer Amusement, or an Adventure at Margate'', written with [[William Augustus Miles]], - the [[Haymarket Theatre|Haymarket]] 1779
* ''Fire and Water, a ballad opera'', - the Haymarket in 1780
* ''Dissipation, a comedy'' -  Drury Lane 1781;
* ''[[The Baron Kinkvervankotsdorsprakingatchdern]], a musical comedy'' - the Haymarket 1781
* ''The Best Bidder, a farce'' - the Haymarket 1782
* ''Reparation, a comedy'' - Drury Lane 1784
* ''Better Late than Never'' - Drury Lane 1790
* ''The Mysteries of the Castle'' - Covent Garden 1795.

